body:
@danielvdende Thanks for filling this enhance issues. 

Registered models' stages and versions change over the course of none, testing, and productizing. For example, you might add/update the description or add a search tag to a registered model in any of these stages.  So freezing a model just because a version of it is a model registry may not be optimal for the model registry workflows. 

Perhaps, once it has transitioned to the "production" stage, then, it might be something to consider. Even in the production stage, though, you can have a new model version that can be transitioned to production, [optionally archiving the older versions](https://mlflow.org/docs/latest/python_api/mlflow.tracking.html#mlflow.tracking.MlflowClient.transition_model_version_stage). So freezing updates here may not allow these workflow operations. 

@mparkhe or @sueann Any insights into this ask?

@dmatrix I think that any freezing behaviour should be tied to a version. But once a model has been registered with a particular version, I personally think it shouldn't be allowed to change any more. Perhaps a description could change, but what we've seen is that it's possible to overwrite existing artifacts in place, without any downstream consumers/users of the model being aware. 

For me, the model registry should function more or less like an artifact store similar to maven central, pypi, etc. from where consumers can obtain artifacts (e.g. models) that will not change. If a change is made, that should result in a new version, not something being changed in an existing one.

Perhaps a model should be frozen, but metadata such as description/tags/etc. should be editable?
